I think you're right, but I think we're still missing what I'm going after. So the question... Okay, yeah. So in your first example, it really gets at this problem. You open symphony at 2 p.m. and call about blinds is up. So let's say you've had three different tasks about blinds. One is shop for blinds. One is... And shop for blinds has a sub-task of measure blinds. And the next task, let's say, is purchase blinds. And the next task is install blinds. And you need the measurements in all three of those steps. But when you create a new task, it lacks the context of the previous task. And I know that you can technically get this from using sub-tasks. But I believe that this is a problem that doesn't have an intuitive solution yet. One that is just effortlessly carried forward. It's sort of like... It's sort of like a pull request for your tasks. They're specced out. They include documentation, screenshots, whatever resources you need. And those resources are carried forward until that thing is complete. And the completion may involve several seemingly unrelated tasks or events or steps. So how do we solve this problem?
OH. Now I get it. This is the real problem. You're not just talking about better execution UI. You're talking about context fragmentation across a workflow of related tasks. The "pull request" metaphor is perfect. In a PR:
The context (issue, design docs, screenshots) lives at the workflow level
Multiple commits reference the same context
Everyone working on it sees the same resources
The context flows through the lifecycle until it's done
Your blinds example exposes the gap:

Task 1: Shop for blinds
  â†³ Subtask: Measure windows
  ğŸ“ Notes: "Living room: 48" x 72", Bedroom: 36" x 60""
  ğŸ”— Link: blinds.com/product-page
  âœ… Complete

Task 2: Purchase blinds
  âŒ Context is ORPHANED - you have to go dig it up
  
Task 3: Install blinds  
  âŒ Context is ORPHANED again
Current workarounds all suck:
Subtasks: Only work if everything is under one parent. But "purchase" and "install" aren't really subtasks of "shop" - they're sequential workflow steps.
Copy-paste context: Manual, error-prone, creates stale copies
Projects: Help group tasks, but don't surface shared context at execution time
Notes/links on each task: Duplication, drift, maintenance burden
The Real Question
How do we create workflow-scoped context that flows through related tasks without requiring heavy manual linking? Potential approaches:
A. Project as Context Container (explicit)
Projects become the context holder
"Blinds Project" has measurements, links, photos
All tasks in project auto-show project context
Pro: Simple mental model
Con: Forces everything into projects (maybe overkill for simple workflows)
B. Task Chains (explicit linking)
"Shop" â†’ "Purchase" â†’ "Install" (like prep/followup but more flexible)
Context flows forward through the chain
Pro: Clear lineage
Con: Requires manual chain creation
C. Context Inheritance (semi-automatic)
When you complete "Shop blinds", system prompts:
"Create next task in this workflow?"
Auto-carries forward context
Pro: Feels effortless
Con: Assumes linear workflows
D. Shared Context Tags (implicit grouping)
Create "Blinds" as a topic/tag
All context lives on the topic, not the tasks
Tasks tagged "Blinds" all show the same shared context
Pro: Flexible, works for non-linear workflows
Con: New concept to learn
E. AI Context Surfacing (smart)
When you open "Purchase blinds", AI detects similarity to "Shop blinds"
Surfaces relevant context automatically
"FYI: You took measurements in a related task [Show]"
Pro: Feels magical
Con: Requires AI, might be wrong
My gut instinct
I think the answer is Projects as Context Containers (Option A), but with a twist: Make project context show up prominently during execution, not just in project view.

